Turns outs I didn&#39;t understand that Netty creates a `NewsAnalyserHandler` for each client that sending messages to the server.

This can be seen in [this log screenshot][1]. I ran 2 instances of the client and for each instance ran, Netty appears to create a `NewsAnalyserHandler`.

My solution was to declare a `LinkedBlockingQueue` in the `NewsAnalyser` class and pass that object as a constructor argument for the `NewsAnalyserHandler`.

I have posted the modified code below.

```java
public final class NewsAnalyser {

    private static final int DEFAULT_PORT = 9001;
    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(NewsAnalyser.class);

    // Newly declared `LinkedBlockingQueue`
    private static final BlockingQueue&lt;NewsItem&gt; newsItemQueue = new LinkedBlockingQueue&lt;&gt;();

    private int port;

    public NewsAnalyser(int port) {
        this.port = port;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        int port = (args.length &gt; 0) ? Integer.parseInt(args[0]) : DEFAULT_PORT;

        new NewsAnalyser(port).run();

    }

    public void run() throws InterruptedException {

        EventLoopGroup bossGroup = new NioEventLoopGroup();
        EventLoopGroup workerGroup = new NioEventLoopGroup();

        try {
            ServerBootstrap b = new ServerBootstrap();
            b.group(bossGroup, workerGroup)
                    .channel(NioServerSocketChannel.class)
                    .childHandler(new ChannelInitializer&lt;SocketChannel&gt;() {

                        @Override
                        protected void initChannel(SocketChannel ch) throws Exception {
                            ch.pipeline().addLast(new NewsItemByteDecoder()).addLast(new ServerResponseEncoder(),
                                    // Passing the `LinkedBlockingQueue` in as a constructor.
                                    new NewsAnalyserHandler(newsItemQueue));
                        }

                    })
                    .option(ChannelOption.SO_BACKLOG, 128)
                    .childOption(ChannelOption.SO_KEEPALIVE, true);

        // start server
          
        } finally {
            // shutdown server
        }
    }
}
```

```java
public class NewsAnalyserHandler extends ChannelInboundHandlerAdapter {

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(NewsAnalyserHandler.class);
    private static final String OK_TO_SEND = &quot;200&quot;;
    private static final String STOP_SENDING = &quot;507&quot;;

    // Declare local `BlockingQueue&lt;T&gt;`
    private BlockingQueue&lt;NewsItem&gt; newsItemQueue;

    // Assign passed in `LinkedBlockingQueue`
    public NewsAnalyserHandler(BlockingQueue&lt;NewsItem&gt; newsItemQueue) {
        this.newsItemQueue = newsItemQueue;
    }

    @Override
    public void channelRead(ChannelHandlerContext ctx, Object msg) throws Exception {

        NewsItem request = (GeneratedNewsItem) msg;

        if (request.getHeadline().equals(&quot;INIT&quot;) &amp;&amp; request.getPriorty() == -1) {
            ctx.write(OK_TO_SEND);
            return;
        }

        if (newsItemQueue.offer(request)) {
            logger.info(&quot;Received news item: {}&quot;, request);
            logger.info(&quot;Sending 200 response&quot;);
            ctx.write(OK_TO_SEND);
        }

        logger.info(&quot;Number of messages: {}&quot;, newsItemQueue.size());
        ReferenceCountUtil.release(msg);

    }
    
    // Channel read complete &amp; exception handling

}

```

After I made the modifications to the code, [this log screenshot][2] shows that the `NewsAnalyserHandler` now functions as expected.


